# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: embedded-book
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:embedded-book/common-protocols] This is a list of common protocols used in embedded systems.
[src:embedded-book/common-protocols] Eventually, this list will become hyperlinks to sources of information on each.
[src:embedded-book/common-protocols] Many of them are byte-stream protocols that can be transmitted by a variety of serial protocols on a variety of hardware.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] Sometimes things will happen in a system when the processor is simply not ready.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] In fact, sometimes things change that require immediate attention.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] Can you imagine, sitting at your PC, that you were to hit buttons on the keyboard, and nothing happens on your computer?
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] Maybe the processor was busy, and it just didn't check to see if you were hitting any buttons at that time.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] The solution to this problem is something called an "Interrupt." Interrupts are events that cause the microprocessor to stop what it is doing, and handle a high-priority task first.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] After the interrupt is handled, the microprocessor goes back to whatever it was doing before.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] In this way, we can be assured that high-priority inputs are never ignored.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] There are two types of interrupts: Hardware and Software.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] Software interrupts are called from software, using a specified command.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] Hardware interrupts are triggered by peripheral devices outside the micro-controller.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] For instance, your embedded system may contain a timer that sends a pulse to the controller every second.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] Your micro-controller would wait until this pulse is received, and when the pulse comes, an interrupt would be triggered that would handle the signal.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] Interrupt Service Routines (ISR) are the portions of the program code that handle the interrupt requests.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] When an Interrupt is triggered (either a hardware or software interrupt), the processor breaks away from the current task, moves the instruction pointer to the ISR, and then continues operation.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] When the ISR has completed, the processor returns execution to the previous location.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] Many embedded systems are called **interrupt driven systems**, because most of the processing occurs in ISRs, and the embedded system spends most of its time in a low-power mode.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] Some people split an ISR into two parts: top-half (fast interrupt handler, First-Level Interrupt Handler (FLIH)) and bottom-half (slow interrupt handler, Second-Level Interrupt Handlers (SLIH)).
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] Top-half is a faster part of ISR which should quickly store minimal information about interrupt and schedule slower bottom-half at a later time.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] We discuss two-level interrupt handling and other ways of writing interrupt handlers in interrupt architecture.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] The "Interrupt Vector Table" is a list of every interrupt service routine.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] It is located at a fixed location in program memory.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] (Some processors expect the interrupt vector table to be a series of "call" instructions, each one followed by the address of the ISR.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] You must make sure that every entry in the interrupt vector table is filled with the address of some actual ISR, even if it means making most of them point to the "do nothing and return from interrupt" ISR.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] The PIC18 and PIC16 series of processors have a single interrupt handler, a single global interrupt enable bit, and a whole array of bits in the interrupt hardware.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] (Confusingly, some people refer to both bits as "flags"—in this section, we refer to the "request attention" bits as flag bits, and the "ignore or not" bits as enable bits).
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] When an interrupt occurs on an 8-bit PICmicro (PIC18 or PIC16), the hardware clears the global interrupt enable bit, then starts running the one and only interrupt handler.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] The interrupt handler software must somehow check all the things that could have possibly caused the interrupt—typically by checking each interrupt flag one by one—and handle each one (if necessary).
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] The 680x0 and x86 and dsPIC and PIC24 and many other processors have many interrupt vectors.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] When some piece of hardware requests attention on such a processor, the hardware vectors to and runs the specific interrupt handler for that particular bit of hardware.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] Many people write interrupt routines in C.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] Alas, there is no standard way to write interrupt handlers in portable C.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] Every C compiler seems to use its own keywords incompatible with the keywords for any other C compiler.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] Even with gcc, the favored interrupt declaration varies from one processor to another.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] Other programmers use C compilers that do not support writing interrupt handlers directly in C.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] An interrupt routine typically begins with a bunch of boilerplate code that pushes the status register and other stuff to the stack, and ends with another bunch of boilerplate code to restore all that stuff so whatever code was interrupted can continue from exactly where it left off.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] That boilerplate code is very different from one processor family to another—and has some key differences from the normal calling convention prologue and epilogue.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] The compiler (or an assembly language programmer) writes in the interrupt vector table a pointer to that interrupt handler.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] One extremely common problem is trying to do "too much" in an interrupt routine.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] Alas, often the symptoms only occur when two different interrupt routines are triggered more-or-less simultaneously, leading to difficult-to-debug intermittent errors and a lot of finger-pointing.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] One common symptom of an interrupt routine (possibly the UART interrupt handler, but often some other seemingly unrelated interrupt routine) taking "too long" is losing some, but not all of the characters in a stream of characters coming in over the UART.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] Because it is difficult to calculate how much time an interrupt handler will take, it is common to directly measure how long interrupt handlers actually take.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] One popular debugging technique is to write interrupt handlers such that the interrupt handler sets a test pin high at the beginning of every interrupt routine, and the interrupt handler clears the test pin low at the end of every interrupt routine.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-interrupts] An o'scope attached to that pin shows the actual execution time of that interrupt handler.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] Embedded Technology is now in its prime and the wealth of knowledge available is mindblowing.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] However, most embedded systems engineers have a common complaint.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] There are no comprehensive resources available over the internet which deal with the various design and implementation issues of this technology.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] Intellectual property regulations of many corporations are partly to blame for this and also the tendency to keep technical know-how within a restricted group of researchers.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] Before embarking on the rest of this book, it is important first to cover exactly what embedded systems are, and how they are used.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] This wikibook will attempt to cover a large number of topics, some of which apply only to embedded systems, but some of which will apply to nearly all computers (embedded or otherwise).
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] As such, there is a chance that some of the material from this book will overlap with material from other wikibooks that are focused on topics such as low-level computing, assembly language, computer architecture, etc.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] But we will first start with the basics, and attempt to answer some questions before the book actually begins.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] The first question that needs to be asked, is "What exactly is an embedded computer?" An embedded computer is frequently a computer that is implemented for a particular purpose.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] In contrast, an average PC computer usually serves a number of purposes: checking email, surfing the internet, listening to music, word processing, etc...
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] However, embedded systems usually only have a single task, or a very small number of related tasks that they are programmed to perform.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] Every home has several examples of embedded computers.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] Any appliance that has a digital clock, for instance, has a small embedded micro-controller that performs no other task than to display the clock.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] Modern cars have embedded computers onboard that control such things as ignition timing and anti-lock brakes using input from a number of different sensors.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] Embedded computers rarely have a generic interface, however.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] Even if embedded systems have a keypad and an LCD display, they are rarely capable of using many different types of input or output.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] An example of an embedded system with I/O capability is a security alarm with an LCD status display, and a keypad for entering a password.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] In general, an Embedded System: It is a combination of hardware and software that performs a specific task.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] An embedded system can be defined as a control system or computer system designed to perform a specific task.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] Common examples of embedded systems include MP3 players, navigation systems on aircraft and intruder alarm systems.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] An embedded system can also be defined as a single purpose computer.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] Most embedded systems are time critical applications meaning that the embedded system is working in an environment where timing is very important: the results of an operation are only relevant if they take place in a specific time frame.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] An autopilot in an aircraft is a time critical embedded system.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] If the autopilot detects that the plane for some reason is going into a stall then it should take steps to correct this within milliseconds or there would be catastrophic results.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] Embedded systems are considered when the cost of implementing a product designed in software on a microprocessor and some small amount of hardware, is cheaper, more reliable, or better for some other reason than a discrete hardware design.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] It is possible for one small and relatively cheap microprocessor to replace dozens or even hundreds of hardware logic gates, timing circuits, input buffers, output drivers, etc.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] It also happens that one generic embedded system with a standard input and output configuration can be made to perform in a completely different manner simply by changing the software.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] The uses of embedded systems are virtually limitless, because every day new products are introduced to the market that utilize embedded computers in novel ways.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] In recent years, hardware such as microprocessors, microcontrollers, and FPGA chips have become much cheaper.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] So when implementing a new form of control, it's wiser to just buy the generic chip and write your own custom software for it.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] Producing a custom-made chip to handle a particular task or set of tasks costs far more time and money.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] Many embedded computers even come with extensive libraries, so that "writing your own software" becomes a very trivial task indeed.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] From an implementation viewpoint, there is a major difference between a computer and an embedded system.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] Embedded systems are often required to provide ***Real-Time response***.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] A ***Real-Time system*** is defined as a system whose correctness depends on the timeliness of its response.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] Examples of such systems are flight control systems of an aircraft, sensor systems in nuclear reactors and power plants.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] For these systems, delay in response is a fatal error.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] A more relaxed version of ***Real-Time Systems***, is the one where timely response with small delays is acceptable.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] Example of such a system would be the Scheduling Display System on the railway platforms.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] Embedded computers may be economical, but they are often prone to some very specific problems.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] A PC computer may ship with a glitch in the software, and once discovered, a software patch can often be shipped out to fix the problem.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] An embedded system, however, is frequently programmed once, and the software cannot be patched.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] Even if it is possible to patch faulty software on an embedded system, the process is frequently far too complicated for the user.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] Another problem with embedded computers is that they are often installed in systems for which unreliability is not an option.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] For instance, the computer controlling the brakes in your car cannot be allowed to fail under any condition.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] The targeting computer in a missile is not allowed to fail and accidentally target friendly units.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] As such, many of the programming techniques used when throwing together production software cannot be used in embedded systems.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] Reliability must be guaranteed before the chip leaves the factory.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] This means that every embedded system needs to be tested and analyzed extensively.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] An embedded system will have very few resources when compared to full blown computing systems like a desktop computer.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] The memory capacity and processing power in an embedded system is limited.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] It is more challenging to develop an embedded system when compared to developing an application for a desktop system as we are developing a program for a very constricted environment.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] Some embedded systems run a scaled down version of operating system called an RTOS (real time operating system).
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] Embedded systems are playing important roles in our lives every day, even though they might not necessarily be visible.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] Some of the embedded systems we use every day control the menu system on television, the timer in a microwave oven, a cellphone, an MP3 player or any other device with some amount of intelligence built-in.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] In fact, recent poll data shows that embedded computer systems currently outnumber humans in the USA.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] Embedded systems is a rapidly growing industry where growth opportunities are numerous.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] This book is designed to accompany a course of study in computer engineering.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] However, this book will also be useful to any reader who is interested in computers, because this book can form the starting point for a "bottom up" learning initiative on computers.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] It is fundamentally easier to study small, limited, simple computers than it is to start studying the big PC behemoths that we use on a daily basis.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] Many topics covered in this book will be software topics as well, so this book will be the most helpful to people with at least some background in programming (especially C and Assembly languages).
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] Having a prior knowledge of semiconductors and electric circuits will be beneficial, but will not be required.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] Many of the concepts discussed in this book apply equally well, if not better, to Desktop computers than to embedded computers.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] In the general interests of completeness, this book will cover a number of topics that have general relevance to all computers in general.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] Many of the lessons in this book will even be better applied by a desktop computer programmer than by an embedded systems engineer.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] It might be more fair to say that this book is more about "Low Level Computing" than "Embedded Systems".
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] This book will, of course, cover many embedded systems topics that are irrelevant when programming desktop computers, such as cross-compilers, Real-Time Operating Systems, EEPROM storage, code compression, bit-banging serial ports, umbilical development, etc.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] After reading this book, there are a number of potential fields of study to continue learning.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] We try to make this wikibook *language neutral*.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] It is not fair to focus on one language, when all embedded computers can't be programmed in that language.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] However, it is nice to have functional example code in some real language.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-introduction] Also, it is useful to point out some features of popular programming languages that are especially important for embedded systems.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] On an Embedded System, memory is at a premium.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] Some chips, particularly embedded VLSI chips, and low-end microprocessors may only have a small amount of RAM "on board" (built directly into the chip), and therefore their memory is not expandable.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] Other embedded systems have a certain amount of memory, and have no means to expand.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] In addition to RAM, some embedded systems have some non-volatile memory, in the form of miniature magnetic disks, FLASH memory expansions, or even various 3rd-party memory card expansions.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] Keep in mind however, that a memory upgrade on an embedded system may cost more than the entire system itself.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] An embedded systems programmer, therefore, needs to be very much aware of the memory available, and the memory needed to complete a task.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] Memory is frequently broken up into a number of different regions that are set aside for particular purposes.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] Many popular microcontrollers (including the 8051, the Atmel AVR, the Microchip PIC, the Cypress PSoC) have a "Harvard architecture", meaning that programs can only execute out of "ROM".
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] You can copy bytes from ROM (or elsewhere) into RAM, but it's physically impossible to jump or call such "code" in RAM.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] This is exactly the opposite of the situation on desktop computers, where the code you write cannot be executed until after it is copied into RAM.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] A few popular microcontrollers (such as the 68HC11 and 68HC12 and ...) have a unified address space (a "von Neumann architecture").
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] You can jump or call code anywhere (although jumping to an address in I/O space is almost certainly not what you really wanted to do).
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] Often software applications grow and grow.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] Ancient processors (such as the 8085 used on the Mars rover Sojourner) with 16 bit address registers can directly access a maximum of 65 536 locations—however, systems using these processors often have much more physical RAM and ROM than that.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] They use "paging" hardware that swaps in and out "banks" of memory into the directly accessible space.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] Early Microchip PIC processors had 2 completely separate set of "banking registers", one for swapping in different banks of program ROM, the other for swapping in different banks of RAM.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] All too often, programs written for embedded systems grow and grow until they exceed the available program space.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] Most CPUs used in desktop machines have a "memory management unit" (MMU).
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] The MMU handles virtual memory, protects regions of memory used by the OS from untrusted programs, and ...
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] Most embedded systems do not have a MMU.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] We discuss the two versions of Linux that can run on a system that does not have a MMU in Embedded Systems/Linux.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] Reserved memory is memory which is reserved for some purpose like additional software installation and startup.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] Old X86 processors were only 16 bit processors, and if a flat memory scheme was used, those processors would only be able to support 65 Kilobytes of memory.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] The system engineers behind the old 8086 and 80286 processors came up with the idea to segment memory, and use a combination of segment pointers and offset pointers to access an effective 20 bit address range, for a maximum of 1 megabyte of addressable memory.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] New 32 bit processors allow for 4 Gigabytes of addressable memory space, and therefore the segmented memory model was all but abandoned in current 32 bit machines (although the segment registers are still used to implement paging schemes).
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] Memory-Mapped I/O is a mechanism by which the processor performs I/O access by using memory access techniques.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] This is often put into effect because the memory bus is frequently much faster than the I/O bus.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] Another reason that memory mapped I/O might be used is that the architecture in use does not have a separate I/O bus.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] In memory mapped IO, certain range of CPU's address space is kept aside for the external peripherals.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] These locations can be accessed using the same instructions as used for other memory accesses.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] But instead, the read/writes to these addresses are interpreted as access to device rather than a location on the main memory.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] A CPU may expect a particular device at a fixed location or can dynamically assign a space for it.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] The way this works is that memory interfaces are often designed as a bus (a shared communications resource), where many devices are attached.
[src:embedded-book/embedded-systems-memory] These devices are usually arranged as primary and secondary devices, where a primary device can send and receive data from any of the secondary devices.
[src:embedded-book/microprocessor-introduction] Effectively programming an embedded system, and implementing it reliably requires the engineer to know many of the details of the system architecture.
[src:embedded-book/microprocessor-introduction] Section 1 of the Embedded Systems book will cover some of the basics of microprocessor architecture.
[src:embedded-book/microprocessor-introduction] This information might not apply to all embedded computers, and much of it may apply to computers in general.
[src:embedded-book/microprocessor-introduction] This book can only cover some basic concepts, because the actual embedded computers available on the market are changing every day, and it is the engineer's responsibility to find out what capabilities and limitations their particular systems have.
[src:embedded-book/microprocessor-introduction] As manufacturers continue to pack more and more transistors onto a single chip, more and more of the stuff that was once "peripheral logic" has been integrated on the same chip as the CPU.
[src:embedded-book/microprocessor-introduction] A *microcontroller* includes most or all the electronics needed in an embedded system in a single integrated circuit ("chip").
[src:embedded-book/microprocessor-introduction] This list is roughly in order of integration.
[src:embedded-book/microprocessor-introduction] The most highly integrated microcontrollers include all these parts on one chip.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] A **Real-Time Operating System** (RTOS) is a computing environment that reacts to input within a specific time period.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] A real-time deadline can be so small that system reaction appears instantaneous.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] The term real-time computing has also been used, however, to describe "slow real-time" output that has a longer, but fixed, time limit.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] Learning the difference between real-time and standard operating systems is as easy as imagining yourself in a computer game.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] Each of the actions you take in the game is like a program running in that environment.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] A game that has a real-time operating system for its environment can feel like an extension of your body because you can count on a specific "lag time:" the time between your request for action and the computer's noticeable execution of your request.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] A standard operating system, however, may feel disjointed because the lag time is unreliable.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] To achieve time reliability, real-time programs and their operating system environment must prioritize deadline actualization before anything else.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] In the gaming example, this might result in dropped frames or lower visual quality when reaction time and visual effects conflict.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] An operating system is considered real-time if it invariably enables its programs to perform tasks within specific time constraints, usually those expected by the user.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] Chapters in this section will discuss how an RTOS works, some general methods for working with an RTOS, and a few popular RTOSes.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] An RTOS must respond in a timely manner to changes, but that does not necessarily mean that an RTOS can handle a large throughput of data.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] In fact in an RTOS, small response times are valued much higher than computing power, or data speed.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] Sometimes an RTOS will even need to drop data to ensure that it meets its strict deadlines.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] In essence, that provides us with a perfect definition: **an RTOS is an operating system designed to meet strict deadlines.** Beyond that definition, there are few requirements as to what an RTOS must be, or what features it must have.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] Some RTOS implementations are very complete and very robust, while other implementations are very simple, and suited for only one particular purpose.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] An RTOS may be either event-driven or time-sharing.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] An **event-driven RTOS** is a system that changes state only in response to an incoming event.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] A **time-sharing RTOS** is a system that changes state as a function of time.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] To most people, embedded systems are not recognizable as computers.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] Instead, they are hidden inside everyday objects that surround us and help us in our lives.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] Embedded systems typically do not interface with the outside world through familiar personal computer interface devices such as a mouse, keyboard and graphic user interface.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] Instead, they interface with the outside world through unusual interfaces such as sensors, actuators and specialized communication links.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] Real-time and embedded systems operate in constrained environments in which computer memory and processing power are limited.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] They often need to provide their services within strict time deadlines to their users and to the surrounding world.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] It is these memory, speed and timing constraints that dictate the use of real-time operating systems in embedded software.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] The heart of a real-time OS (and the heart of every OS, for that matter) is the **kernel**.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] Now, we will talk about booting and bootloaders later, and we will also devote several chapters to task scheduling.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] So we should mention at least one thing about standard function libraries: In an embedded system, there is rarely enough memory (if any) to maintain a large function library.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] If functions are going to be included, they must be small, and important.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] In an embedded system, frequently the kernel will boot the system, initialize the ports and the global data items.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] Then, it will start the scheduler and instantiate any hardware timers that need to be started.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] After all that, the Kernel basically gets dumped out of memory (except for the library functions, if any), and the scheduler will start running the child tasks.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] In the discussion below, we will focus on the "kernel" — the part of an operating system that provides the most basic services to application software running on a processor.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] The "kernel" of a real-time operating system ("RTOS") provides an "abstraction layer" that hides from application software the hardware details of the processor (or set of processors) upon which the application software will run.
[src:embedded-book/real-time-operating-systems] See Embedded Systems/Common RTOS for a list of common real-time operating systems.
